Durban - Police arrested a man and a woman who were travelling in a hijacked E Class Mercedes Benz along the N2 on Monday. Kyle van Reenen, Marshall Security spokesperson said their security company was alerted to a hijacking that took place in Empangeni, north of KwaZulu-Natal. Van Reenen said the car was fitted with a tracking device and the signal indicated that the car was travelling on the N2 towards Durban.  To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window. A man and a woman were arrested at Tongaat Toll plaza after the car they were travelling in was hijacked in Empangeni. Video: Supplied “Members of the Marshall Security Special Operations Team, Z2 Security, HAWKS Security and the SAPS positioned themselves on the N2 at the Tongaat Toll plaza. Members of the SAPS Umhlali K9 unit picked up visuals of the vehicle and began following it from the Umhlali area. When the vehicle entered the tollgate it was brought to a stop and a male and female suspect were arrested,” van Reenen said. The car and the arrested man and woman are in police custody for further investigations and processing. Daily News